# unique categorical values

def unique_categorical(cat_dataset, dataset):
    for col in cat_dataset:
        print(f'{col}: {dataset[col].nunique()}')
        

print(f'Train data unique values:{unique_categorical(train_data_cat_c, train_data)}\n')
print(f'Test data unique values:{unique_categorical(test_data_cat_c, test_data)}\n')

4.4 Standarization for numeric data¶

Variables will be on the same scale, so the model will not favor those with baseline values (e.g. GrLivArea).

We need to fill or delete missing data. In our solution we fill missing data by median

In [41]:
train_stand = train_data[['OverallQual', 'GrLivArea', 'GarageCars', 'GarageArea',
                             'TotalBsmtSF', '1stFlrSF', 'FullBath', 'TotRmsAbvGrd', 'YearBuilt']]

train_stand = train_stand.fillna(train_stand.median())

# Preparing etry datasets
X = train_data_num_c.drop(columns=['SalePrice'])
# logharytmic transform SalePrice because as we seen, have a lot of outliers
# the model will more stable
y = np.log(train_data_num_c['SalePrice']) 

# test_data set standard (because don't have SalePrice column)
X_test = test_data_num_c.copy()

# Filling missing data by median
X = X.fillna(X.median())
X_test = X_test.fillna(X_test.median())

# Group on train and validation set
# random_state changed to 1
X_train, X_val, y_train, y_val = train_test_split(X, y, random_state=1)

# Train Random Forest model
# n_estimators changed to 100 and random_state 0
rf_model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=0)
rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# prediction for validation set
val_predictions = rf_model.predict(X_val)

# RMSE for logharytmic values
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_val, val_predictions))
print(f"Validation RMSE: {rmse:.6f}")

# prediction on test data set and converting the results to oryginal scale
test_predictions = np.exp(rf_model.predict(X_test))

Validation RMSE: 0.142402

Explanation of changes:¶

  1. Taking the Log of the Target Variable (SalePrice):
  • Log transformation: Applying the logarithm to the target variable (here SalePrice) helps stabilize the model, especially for data with a distribution that is highly skewed or contains extreme values (outliers). This reduces the impact of large values on the model, which can improve its accuracy.
  • Why: Regression models, including Random Forest, are better at dealing with symmetric distributions, and taking the logarithm makes the target variable more normally distributed, which leads to more accurate predictions.
  1. Splitting the data into training and validation sets (train_test_split):
  • Random splitting of training and validation data: Using train_test_split allows you to train a model on one part of the data (training set) and then evaluate the model on the other part (validation set). This allows us to assess how well the model generalizes to new data.
  • Why: We avoid overfitting, which can lead to very good results on the training set but poor predictions on new data.

  1. StandardScaler is necessary in Random Forest Regression

  2. Using Random Forest with the right parameters:

  • Setting the right model parameters: Such as n_estimators=100, random_state=0, which help ensure the model is stable and able to learn on large data sets.
  • Why: These parameters help control the number of trees in the forest and ensure the repeatability of the results (thanks to random_state), which is important when testing models and comparing results.

Explanation of code details:¶

  • n_estimators: This parameter determines the number of decision trees in the random forest. Each tree in the forest is built independently and then averaged to produce the final prediction. Increasing the number of trees (n_estimators) typically leads to better performance, as it reduces overfitting and improves the robustness of the model. However, higher values of n_estimators also increase computational cost. In this case, n_estimators=100 means that the random forest consists of 100 decision trees.
  • random_state: This parameter controls the randomness of the random forest algorithm. It is used to set the seed for the random number generator, which ensures reproducibility of the results. By setting a specific value for random_state, you make sure that the random splitting of data and other random aspects of the algorithm remain consistent across different runs. In this case, random_state=0 sets the seed for the random number generator to 0.
